<article class="border-l-4 border-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] pl-6">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">July 11, 2026</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4">Ran the Cluster A leg of the reciprocal inbound-link sweep called for in <code>docs/marketing/LP-CLUSTER-PLAN-2026-06.md</code>. Cluster A is fully deployed (A1–A4); A2 had inbound links wired the day it shipped, so this commit adds inbound links for <strong>A1</strong> (<code>/breeder-management-software</code>), <strong>A3</strong> (<code>/horse-breeding-software</code>), and <strong>A4</strong> (<code>/breeder-crm</code>) across the high-authority surfaces that should send them traffic and ranking signal.</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
    <p>
      <strong>Why.</strong> Geographic-page experience taught us the metro-island failure mode — pages without incoming internal links don't get crawled often, don't pass authority, and don't compound. The LP cluster plan extends the geo reciprocal-backlink rule to LP clusters. Doing the sweep atomically per cluster (rather than per page) keeps the diff reviewable and avoids multi-agent contention on the same files.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>What changed.</strong>
    </p>

